<PubmedArticleSet>
<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">23053133</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2013</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>05</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>28</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1439-6327</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>113</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2013</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>European journal of applied physiology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Eur J Appl Physiol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Long-term creatine supplementation improves muscular performance during resistance training in older women.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>987</StartPage><EndPage>996</EndPage><MedlinePgn>987-96</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1007/s00421-012-2514-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This study examined the effects of long-term creatine supplementation combined with resistance training (RT) on the one-repetition maximum (1RM) strength, motor functional performance (e.g., 30-s chair stand, arm curl, and getting up from lying on the floor tests) and body composition (e.g., fat-free mass, muscle mass, and % body fat using DEXA scans) in older women. Eighteen healthy women (64.9 &#xb1; 5.0 years) were randomly assigned in a double-blind fashion to either a creatine (CR, N = 9) or placebo (PL, N = 9) group. Both groups underwent a 12-week RT program (3 days week(-1)), consuming an equivalent amount of either creatine (5.0 g day(-1)) or placebo (maltodextrin). After 12 week, the CR group experienced a greater (P &lt; 0.05) increase (&#x394;%) in training volume (+164.2), and 1RM bench press (+5.1), knee extension (+3.9) and biceps curl (+8.8) performance than the PL group. Furthermore, CR group gained significantly more fat-free mass (+3.2) and muscle mass (+2.8) and were more efficient in performing submaximal-strength functional tests than the PL group. No changes (P &gt; 0.05) in body mass or % body fat were observed from pre- to post-test in either group. These results indicate that long-term creatine supplementation combined with RT improves the ability to perform submaximal-strength functional tasks and promotes a greater increase in maximal strength, fat-free mass and muscle mass in older women.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Aguiar</LastName><ForeName>Andreo Fernando</ForeName><Initials>AF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Center of Biological and Health Sciences, North University of Paran&#xe1; UNOPAR, Avenue Paris, 675 Jardim Piza, Londrina, PR 86041-120, Brazil. andreoaguiar@hotmail.com</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Janu&#xe1;rio</LastName><ForeName>Renata Selvatici Borges</ForeName><Initials>RS</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Junior</LastName><ForeName>Raymundo Pires</ForeName><Initials>RP</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gerage</LastName><ForeName>Aline Mendes</ForeName><Initials>AM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Pina</LastName><ForeName>F&#xe1;bio Luiz Cheche</ForeName><Initials>FL</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>do Nascimento</LastName><ForeName>Matheus Amarante</ForeName><Initials>MA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Padovani</LastName><ForeName>Carlos Roberto</ForeName><Initials>CR</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cyrino</LastName><ForeName>Edilson Serpeloni</ForeName><Initials>ES</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D013485">Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2012</Year><Month>10</Month><D